text: Total Synthesis of the Monomeric Unit of Lomaiviticin A § § K. C. Nicolaou,* Qifeng Chen, ABSTRACT: The architecturally symmetrical and synthetically challenging marine natural products lomaiviticins A and B present alluring synthetic targets due to their molecular complexity, potent antitumor properties, and natural scarcity. Herein, we report the total the fully glycosylated monomeric unit of lomaiviticin A, monolomaiviticin A. The retrosynthetically derived synthetic strategy relied on an intramolecular palladium-catalyzed coupling reaction to complete the tetracyclic aglycon scaﬀold and gold-promoted glycosylations to install the synthetically challenging α- and β-glycoside moieties of the target molecule. This accomplish- ment paves a path for the eventual total synthesis of lomaiviticins A and B and opens opportunities for biological investigations within this family of compounds.

A plethora of biologically interesting natural products have been isolated from a wide variety of marine organisms, among which is the orange ascidian Polysyncraton lithostrotum.1 From the latter were discovered the extremely potent antitumor antibiotics enediyne agent namenamicin2 (1, Figure 1) and dimeric diazobenzoﬂuorene glycosides lomaiviticins A (2, Figure 1) and B (3, Figure 1),3 whose complete absolute conﬁgurations were subsequently determined by the Herzon team.4 Their natural scarcities, together with their intriguing biological proﬁles against cancer cell lines,2,3,5 have attracted signiﬁcant attention from synthetic organic chemists with several notable accomplishments having been made already.6 We have recently reported the total synthesis and full structural elucidation of namenamicin (1).6a The rather intimidating lomaiviticin A (2) and its sibling, molecular structures of lomaiviticin B (3), however, present unprecedented synthetic challenges,7 although a number of important advances have been reported toward their total synthesis.7,8 Furthermore, the total synthesis of kinamycins C (5), F (6), and J (7; monomeric relatives of lomaiviticins A and B, Figure 1) have been accomplished.7c,9 Although related to the previously synthesized kinamycins C (5), F (6), and J (7), mono- lomaiviticin A (4), a possibly naturally occurring molecule not two unusual glycosidic bonds yet discovered, with its constitutes a novel and challenging synthetic target. Herein, we report fully glycosylated mono- lomaiviticin A (4, Figure 1) as a prelude to the total synthesis of the naturally occurring lomaiviticins A (2) and B (3). monolomaiviticin A (4). Each of the two glycosidic bonds had their own challenge. The pyrrolosamine carbohydrate moiety had to be installed through a β-glycosidic bond (not the favorite anomer in the absence of a substituent at the C2 position of the sugar),10 whereas the L-oleandrose glycoside unit had to be introduced onto a tertiary alkoxy residue of the tetracyclic carbohydrate acceptor (often not an easy task).7a,8h,11 With these challenges in mind, monolomaiviticin A (4) was retrosynthetically traced back to its diazo-bis- methoxy, bis-MOM, bis-TES protected precursor 8 (Figure 2), whose transformation to 4 would rely on oxidative conversion of its bis-methoxy system to a quinone moiety, followed by sequential cleavage of the TES and MOM protective groups. Precursor 8 was to be obtained from key tetracyclic aglycon 9 through sequential glycosylation with glycosyl donors 10 and 11, the latter to be derived from readily available building blocks 1512 and 16,6b respectively, as shown in Figure 2. Disconnection of the indicated carbon−carbon (intramolecular palladium-catalyzed coupling) and carbon−oxygen bonds (allylic oxidation) of aglycon 9 led to bromoketone 12 as a potential precursor, whose disconnection at the indicated carbon−carbon bond traced it back to bromoaldehyde 13 and vinyl iodide 14, as shown in Figure 2.

The construction of tetracyclic aglycon 9 started with the previously known and easily prepared building blocks 178d and 18,8d as summarized in Scheme 1. Thus, cyclohexanone 178d was converted to its enol triﬂate 19 (PhNTf2, LiHMDS, 77% yield) and the latter was transformed to the corresponding iodide 14 through Reisman’s elegant Ni-catalyzed vinyl triﬂate−iodide transfer conditions [Ni(OAc)2 ·4H2O, NaI, Zn cat., cod cat., DMAP cat.] in 82% yield.13 In parallel, naphthoquinone 188d was converted to the desired bromoal- dehyde 13 through a reduction (Na2S2O4)/MOM protection

(MOMCl, i-Pr2NEt) sequence in 82% overall yield, as shown iodide 14 was then treated with tert- in Scheme 1. Vinyl butyllithium in the presence of TMEDA, and to the so- generated cyclohexenyllithium intermediate was added alde- hyde 13, aﬀording secondary alcohol 20 (73% yield, inconsequential mixture of diastereoisomers), whose exposure to NMO/TPAP cat. furnished bromoketone 12 in 89% yield. With bromoketone 12 readily available, the next task became the closure of the remaining cyclopentenone ring through an intramolecular carbon−carbon bond formation. To this end, we examined ﬁrst Herzon’s pioneering conditions7c,8e [Pd- (OAc)2, polymer-supported PPh3, Ag2CO3, PhMe, reﬂux, see Table 1, entry 1, 23% yield] and observed the formation of the expected product 21, albeit in a compromised yield. In order to result we undertook a systematic improve upon this investigation varying the palladium source, ligand, base, solvent, and reaction temperature. Table 1 summarizes the results of this optimization study. Thus, changing the ligand from the above conditions7c,8e from PS−PPh3 to SPhos14 as a ligand proved futile, as shown in Table 1 (entry 2, 10% yield of cyclized product). Switching the ligand to BI-DIME15 and lowering the reaction temperature to 80 °C improved the yield of the product to 33% (Table 1, entry 3). It was also found that Pd2(dba)3 was a better source of palladium than Pd(OAc)2 in this reaction at 80 °C, leading to a 37% yield of product 21 (Table 1, entry 4), while the use of Et3N as a base, instead of Ag2CO3, resulted in a slightly lower yield (32% yield, Table 1, entry 5). K2CO3 as a base outperformed both Ag2CO3 and Et3N, improving the yield of the reaction to 45% (Table 1, entry 6). Finally, changing the solvent from toluene to DMF, while maintaining the other parameters the same, resulted in 40% yield (Table 1, entry 7), whereas switching to dioxane as the solvent and keeping the other parameters the same proved superior to all conditions tried, furnishing 73% of the desired product 21 (Table 1, entry 8).16

Having optimized the crucial palladium-catalyzed intra- molecular closure of the ﬁnal ring of the targeted intermediate 21, and going back to Scheme 1, we then proceeded to install the required hydroxyl group at C1 of the molecule. This goal was achieved through exposure of 21 to silica gel-supported 17 and pyridine at elevated temperature (dioxane, sealed SeO2 tube, 110 °C), leading to the corresponding allylic alcohol 22 in 43% yield [87% yield based on recovered starting material including the downstream reduction/oxidation sequence (DIBAL-H, MnO2, see Scheme 1)] as a mixture of inconsequential C1-diastereoisomers. Along with the latter, however, was also produced enedione 24 as an overoxidized byproduct contaminated with, and inseparable from, starting material 21 in a combined yield of 51%, 21:24 ca. 1.8:1, as shown in Scheme 1. Treatment of this mixture with DIBAL-H, led to a mixture of dihydroxy compound 25 and however, monohydroxy intermediate 25a in quantitative yield (25a:25 ca. 1.8:1). Oxidation of this mixture (MnO2) resulted in a separable mixture of the desired hydroxyenone product 22 (33% yield) and starting material enone 21 (61% yield), chromatographically puriﬁed. The required pyrrolosamine and oleandrose glycosyl donors 10 and 11, equipped with the appropriate o-alkynylbenzoate moieties according to our projected gold-promoted glyco- sylations,20 were synthesized as summarized in Scheme 2A,B, respectively. The employment of N-Alloc protected mono- methyl amino group within glycosyl donor 10 was intended in order to avoid undesired basicity that would interfere with the pending gold-promoted glycosylation reactions.21 The con- struction of pyrrolosamine glycosyl donor 10 (Scheme 2A) started with glycal (15),12 whose selective protection at the allylic hydroxyl group with the sterically demanding TBDPS group (TBDPSCl, imidazole) furnished hydroxy TBDPS silyl ether 26 in 88% yield. The bulky TBDPS group was expected to favor the pending delivery of the iodine residue from the opposite face of the molecule as desired. Silyl ether 26 was then treated sequentially with Tf2O/pyridine (triﬂate for- mation), NaN3 (azide formation with inversion of conﬁg- uration), and PPh3 (azide reduction), aﬀording primary amine 27 in 72% overall yield for the three steps, as shown in Scheme 2A. The amino group of the latter was then protected as an Alloc derivative (AllocCl, NaHCO3) and methylated (MeI, NaH) to aﬀord intermediate 28 in 85% overall yield. The latter was subjected to iodoacetoxylation conditions22 with NIS in the two the presence of AcOH yielding a mixture of

diastereomeric iodoacetates 29 and 30 in a ratio of ca. 1:1.2 in 83% combined yield and with the major isomer 30 being the one required and expected by virtue of the inﬂuencing steric eﬀect of the bulky TBDPS group on the iodination stereoselectivity. The minor isomer 29 could, in principle, be reverted back to starting material 28 for recycling. The installment of the bulky α-iodo substituent at the C2 position of glycosyl donor 10 was envisioned to enhance the desired β- anomeric selectivity of the pending glycosylation, which would have been rather challenging without it.22,23 The acetate group within the desired iodo intermediate 30 was cleaved ·H2O), and the resulting lactol was coupled with (NH2NH2 o-alkynylbenzoic acid 3124 (EDCI·HCl, i-Pr2NEt, DMAP cat.) to aﬀord benzoate 32 in 89% overall yield for the two steps, as shown in Scheme 2A. The sterically demanding TBDPS group of the latter was then replaced with the much smaller acetate residue (TBAF, NH4F; then AcOH, EDCI·HCl, i-Pr2NEt, DMAP cat., 78% overall yield for the two steps) with the intention of facilitating the pending glycosylation by reducing steric hindrance at the anomeric center. The oleandrose glycosyl donor 11 was prepared from building block 166b as summarized in Scheme 2B. In considering the projected synthetic steps beyond the crucial glycosylations, we chose the formate ester as the preferred protecting group for intermediate 33.18a,25 Thus, the free hydroxyl moiety of treatment of hydroxy benzoate 33 with formic pivalic anhydride [HC(O)OPiv]26 in the presence of pyridine and DMAP cat. furnished oleandrose glycosyl donor 11 in 95% yield, as shown in Scheme 2B.

With appropriately protected tetracyclic aglycon 9 and glycosyl donors 10 and 11 in hand, we proceeded toward the synthesis of monolomaiviticin A (4) as summarized in Scheme 3. Thus, coupling of 9 with iodo glycosyl donor 10 in the presence of gold(I) promoter Ph3PAuNTf2 furnished regioselectively the two anomeric products with the desired β-anomer as the predominant isomer (34, α:β ca. 1:6, ca. 2.3:1 dr at C1, α-anomer not shown) as planned and anticipated. Radical-mediated deiodination of this mixture at low temper- ature (Et3B, O2, n-Bu3SnH, −60 °C) led to the pair of separable C1 diastereomeric (inconsequential) β-anomers 35a [(1S)-isomer]and 35b [(1R)-isomer] in 19% and 37% overall yield, respectively, from 9, as shown in Scheme 3. The two C1- isomeric β-anomers 35a and 35b were separately processed forward until they merged to a single C1 ketone precursor later in the sequence (see Scheme 3). Finally, the targeted monomeric lomaiviticin A (4) was generated from 8 through a three-step sequence involving oxidative conversion of the dimethoxy benzenoid system to the corresponding quinone moiety [(NH4)2Ce(NO3)6, 40, 54% yield] and cleavage, ﬁrst of the silyl ethers (Et3N·3HF) and thence of ·Et2O, 56% overall yield the MOM protecting groups (MgBr2 for the two steps), as shown in Scheme 3. Preliminary biological evaluation of monomeric lomaiviticin A (4) revealed low micromolar potencies against breast cancer cells KPL-4 (IC50 = 4.242 μM), triple negative breast cancer cells (MDA-MB-468, IC50 = 1.404 μM), and immortalized human embryonic kidney cells (HEK293, IC50 = 7.848 μM), indicating some diﬀerentiation of the compound between cancerous and immortalized cells. These results also point to signiﬁcant the monomer as compared to the naturally occurring lomaiviticin A (CCRFCEM, IC50 = 0.4 nM; A549, IC50 = 3.5 nM; DU145, IC50 = 0.67 nM; HTB161, IC50 = 0.007 nM),3 a common phenomenon for natural or designed bioactive molecules,31 although the diﬀerences in cell lines and assays should be a factor to consider in these comparisons. Given the mechanistic loss of antitumor activity of

model provided by the Herzon group5 for the double stranded DNA cleavage by lomaiviticin A, the reported and observed signiﬁcant diﬀerences of IC50 values for the parent lomaiviticin A (2) and its monomeric version (4) is not surprising. It rather bolsters the proposed bis-radical based mechanism of DNA cleavage by the natural product and justiﬁes the pursuit of dimeric rather than monomeric analogues, if one is aiming for higher rather than lower potencies. In conclusion, we developed a modular asymmetric total synthesis of the monomeric unit of lomaiviticin A, mono- lomaiviticin A (4), featuring an intramolecular Heck reaction, and two stereoselective, gold(I)-promoted glycosylation reactions. The reported synthesis renders this molecule (4) available for biological investigations and paves the way for the total synthesis of lomaiviticins A (2, Figure 1) and B (3, Figure strategy involving a 1), presumably through a similar dimerization at some point in the sequence, as a means to reach their more complex structures.
